I've looked at the website for a grand 5 minutes so far, just skimming what's on each page, so take this for what it's worth. 

 I'm currently not seeing resources specific to international students or those with ADHD (maybe I'm missing them?) - which are two identities I have, that I was hoping to learn more about in this website (my suspected ADHD does not have a diagnosis yet, was hoping you would have female-centered resources on that to help me navigate living with these challenges while I await an assessment.).  I have Generalized Anxiety, so I'll check out what you have for that. 

I personally don't need the basics of "what is mental health" - I'm definitely further along in my journey of learning about this stuff, so I'll likely skip a lot of the content that seems too introductory.  That's not a jab at you including it - I know it needs to be in there.  The TED talks currently seem the most useful, only a couple of modules seem useful to me, based on their titles. 

I also, in general, think that online resources can only do so much - I fundamentally understand these topics quite well  but at this point, I just need a therapist (I think we all do) and I'd rather see money go into making therapy appointments affordable instead of more online resources. I've done the Ontario program for mental health (Bounce Back?). I've been in a chronic pain program and learned CBT multiple times....  I "get it". And also, I have gleaned what I can from that rather generic approach, and it has given me new language and helped in some ways. But I still struggle with some things and just need individualized assistance at this point. Not generic information.

The site overall looks great and I love the variety of resources available; however, I was hoping to see modules or sources specifically for LGBTQIA+ students. Unless I missed them, there did not appear to be such sources. I think the site could also benefit from a "Search" function, wherein users can type in a keyword for a specific resource they are searching for that can make it easier to pinpoint the exact resource they need at that time. Again, perhaps the site does have such a function, though I could not find it. Additionally, I could not find an accessibility function. Although I don't need it myself, I know many disabled students could benefit from a function that has the contents of the screen read out loud to them (i.e., those who are blind or visually impaired). I know most students with such disabilities likely have a built-in app on their device for screen-reading, but those apps can be quite costly and not all disabled students have the funds to purchase them. I think a website that has a mission of promoting accessible mental health resources to a diverse student population would benefit from somehow adding a screen-reading/text-to-voice function as I have seen other websites implement.

It's great for people unfamiliar with mental health, but not for intermediate/advanced knowledge on mental health. I would love a part of the website for management of chronic mental illness. Yes, I know the therapies and actions to get better, but there's a fatigue associated with constant regulation and monitoring of your mental health. There are long-term challenges that I don't see addressed in most mental health services. I know this site doesn't replace healthcare services, but I find it difficult to find perseverance strategies or pacing strategies or body battery strategies or shifting personal perceptions of your future (to account for chronic mental illness). The chronic part of the mental illness affecting general health is not widely discussed, but reactions/immediate aid to mental "unwellness" is over-advertised.

COMM:
The "navigation" graphics, which contain descriptions for each tab's content, are located at the bottom of the pages. This makes it less obvious what the purpose of each tab is (for example, I was wondering what the difference was between the modules and courses, and while the "navigation" graphic explains this sufficiently, I didn't see it at first). Not only that, but with the way the descriptions are embedded into the buttons (eg., "TEDTALK Library. A curated directory of..."), my screen reader was unable to read the words out to me (alt text on images is important!!!), and those descriptions don't seem to be located anywhere else. I think it is important to give those descriptions at the top of each tab, respectively.

I also find that the decorative headers font isn't the easiest to read - I don't feel that it is the best choice for headers that are so instrumental to navigating the site! (It's very pretty though! If you had less-essential content that you wanted to highlight/stylize using this font, that could be nice!)

I would also recommend adding something on the home page - maybe after the "Welcome Back" message, and before the "Work in Progress" section - to remind users of the general contents of the website. Since I had to scroll down past that lovely banner graphic to see the text on the homepage, I could no longer see the tabs at the top... so if the tabs don't stay visible throughout scrolling, I think it would be helpful to summarize the options/content/general website purpose, even just with the first sentence of the "About" page. I was expecting the "About" to be more about the creation of the website and who's behind it, rather than the place I should go to figure out what the website is overall!

Finally, I wanted to mention that I like the explanation about the efficacy of mental health apps and the lack of empirical research supporting them! It helped to convince me that your website is a trustworthy one!

On this survey, there are a few things that could be made clearer. One question, on the scale of responses on the negative side, it goes from never to "Several days" but leaves no option for "just a few days," which is the response I really wanted. 

For the question which has two parts (how stressful + how often was the stress), it's not clear to me on the second part: Should I be saying how often was the stress through the entire time period (so, how many exams, for instance), OR, how often relative to the number of times it happened. (So, even if I only had, say, 3 exams, if the stress was for all 3 exams, then I would say "all the time" because it was 100% of the instances, even though there were very few instances.)

Another question talks about my comfort talking to friends, and other questions about family. In my life, I really only have two sources of mental health help: my one very good friend who's 75 years old, and my spouse. Where does spouse fit in -- friends or family? To further complicate my position, my dad -- who's family -- is a very poor source of mental health help for me. So if I answer negatively about family, that reflects how I feel about him, but if I add in my spouse as family, he brings the average way up. But, if I add him in as a friend, well, he actually brings DOWN the average relative to my very good 75-year-old friend. I don't know the solution to this, but you see my predicament. 

I am BLOWN AWAY by the CBT toolkit on the network. I love it so much. Something negative happened in my life just before Christmas holidays, and boy, it took me some time to recover. I never had the language for it, but turns out, it was a cognitive distortion -- maybe emotional reasoning, definitely overgeneralization -- and now I have the language for it. And, I think it's connected to my deep-seated belief about myself, about being inadequate, which might stem from me being born out of wedlock, whereas my 3 siblings were born after my parents were married. So anyway, thank you to the network for giving me the tools, language, and motivation to think about these things.

A reminder of my « incredible » situation as an international student in Quebec for the past 11 years: 2024 was the worst year of my immigration here. When your thesis advisor, your employer, your landlord (who threatened me with eviction on several occasions) and even ordinary people tell you all day long to “get the hell out of here” (with an openly racist background) because, in their eyes, you're not a “good immigrant”, it clearly doesn't make you want to stay here after making more than a decade of inhuman sacrifices. If all goes well, I'll finish my thesis this year and leave this province definitively. Fortunately, I still manage to project myself positively into the future, and I hope to move to the English-speaking side of Canada (or USA) to share the fruit of my doctoral work (a thesis on totalitarianism covering Fascist Italy, Nazi Germany, the Stalinist USSR, but also the Transhumanist United States since Operation Warp Speed decreed in 2020 that represents the biggest crimes against humanity since the end of the Second World War with regard to the Nuremberg Code... which is at the root of the harassment/mobbing/ostracism I've been enduring for the past five years without interruption).
